Audiences for contemporary German film and television are becoming increasingly transnational, and depictions of German cultural history are moving beyond the typical post-war focus on Germany's problematic past. Entertaining German Culture explores this radical shift, building on recent research into transnational culture to argue that a new process of internal and external cultural reabsorption is taking place through areas of mutually assimilating cultural exchange such as streaming services, an increasingly international film market, and the import and export of Anglo-American media formats.  afunded by Ludwig Fund at New College, Oxford & Humanities Institute, University College Dublin  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aCostabile-Heming, Carol Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEhrig, Stephan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEhrig, Stephan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEspinoza Garrido, Felipe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalle, Randall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevine-West, Bridget, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNickl, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaper, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaper, Benjamin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSilos Ribas, Lorena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/